betterquesting:10.desc:8: The standar vanilla brick! - These are used to build GregTech steam machines, and after baking, the brick can be further processed into Fireclay, a material heat-resistant enough to allow steel production.

Simple compressed clay, with this, you can build coke furnaces, special buildings for turning wood into charcoal, and ordinary coals into more energy-efficient coal cokes.
The furnace will also produce an output of Creosote Oil, which can later be used as a form of fuel!

To build the oven, you will need 108 compressed clay.
Just punch some trees!
Only source of Tin, Gold, and Gemstones at the String tier.
Highest Stone to Iron ratio at String level. Very small Copper by-product.

Highest stone to Copper ratio at String level.
The Enargite dust cannot be processed until you reach MV with GregTech Machines.
Roughly a 2:1 ratio of Copper to Iron.

Source of all kinds of mixed sands, useful for Porcelain, Tofu, and more.
Also includes Oilsands, Silicon and Quartz sands.
Source of pebbles - use this to get stone when there's none around, or to make decorative stones like Marble and Basalt.
Source of vanilla plant seeds, this will be the start of your agriculture!
Source of vanilla trees - these are excellent sources of wood, and Oak tree leaves even drop apples.

The GregTech mod introduces various tools that are used in recipes, such as saws, knives, screwdrivers, and more.

These items are always displayed in JEI as 'Darmstadtium <tool name>', e.g. 'Darmstadtium Knife', but by looking at recipes for the item, you can discover all the materials it can be made from.

To make patterns and forms you need a knife - at this point, it is likely that your only knife-capable material available will be Flint, which should be displayed first for the knife recipes.

Note: Most 'info' style quests like this one will have this same icon, but just use a checkbox objective.
Make sure you read the text of info quests if you feel stuck.
These patterns are required for nearly all basic tool construction.
The humble beginning to making a Coke Oven, Blast Furnace, and any other clay bricks.
The saw is used to get more planks from wood, or to make forms from planks.
Just a faceless wooden form. Can be carved into a form for bricks or tool parts.

A combination of sand, gravel, and clay formed into the shape of a brick!
This makes for a very heat-resistant brick when baked, that can stay solid next to most early molten metals.

This quest can also be completed with Porcelain, an equally useful substance!

Your first step toward casting metal tool parts.

This quest is completable with either seared bricks or porcelain bricks.

The basic brick used to build a coke oven.

A single coke oven requires 108 bricks.
This block is the cornerstone for GregTech's steam machines, along with bronze plates.

A baked brick, reduced to dust by a machine or patience with a mortar.
This is a vital component of Fireclay, the base component of Blast Furnaces which allow primitive steel production.

A single furnace requires 72 brick dust.

Compressed Fireclay, ready for baking into bricks and for use in the Blast Furnace!

A single furnace requires 144 bricks.
Primitive furnace for steel production, requires charcoal or coke for fuel and iron to produce steel.
To build a coke oven, you need to form a 3x3x3 cube of Coke Oven bricks, and right click the middle of any of the sides with the Engineer's Hammer.
A thick flowing liquid used for impregnating wood, and as a low quality fuel source.
Place wood logs in a coke oven to convert them into charcoal.
Build one of various seared or porcelain tanks to hold lava as a particularly hot fuel for the melter.

The seared or porcelain heater provides limited heat for your melter, but works on conventional fuels.
It can melt copper, tin, and gold, letting you get started with the basics, without the need for any lava.

A small melter for heating metals beyond their melting point.
You can attach Faucets or other liquid manipulators such as pumps directly to this block in order to retrieve the molten metal.

Note: You can only have a single liquid inside the melter at once!
Drain your excess into a tank, or cast it into ingots.
You must use some type of fuel for the melter. Early on, lava is recommended as it can be made by simply melting stone in a Crucible (see the Ex Nihilo quests for more information).
Compressed wood pulp in the shape of a plate. Required for simple logistics using conveyors and item routers.
Required for advanced redstone gates.

A one-directional conveyor.

This block moves items on top of it in a single direction.
Its direction can be adjusted using an Engineer's Hammer, and can even go up or down by shift-right clicking with the hammer.

The conveyor will auto-insert into inventories such as chests if it pushes the item directly into the block.

A trap door on the conveyor inserts items straight down into inventories (or other conveyors).

This can be used, along with filtered inventories, to easily fill a row of Drawer blocks with the right materials from a mixed-item conveyor.
Pulls items from inventories on the extractor side and pushes them onto a conveyor belt.
A space-efficient conveyor that pulls items straight up.

A filtered item routing system!

Sends items in one of six directions, based on the filters setup in the router.

Items first check for a whitelisted side, and go there if possible.
If there is no inventory, or the inventory is full on the whitelisted side, they will go to a random side without any whitelist, assuming there is an available inventory.

If there are no available outputs (e.g. if all sides are blocked, or the inventories attached are all full) the item will not enter the item router.

Splits incoming item stacks with a roughly 50/50 chance.

It is recommended to use an Item Router for more specific splitting.
A simple wooden gear for early logistics. This piece can be automated with the Immersive Engineering Metal Press when you get access to Forge Energy (FE).

These are the gates available in standard Minecraft, without any mods. In this pack, however, they have been replaced with the versions from the Simple Logic Gates mod, which allows you to place the gates on walls and ceilings!
Gates for logical operations. Descriptions of each type available on the individual quests, for those who are not familiar with the naming!

The repeater is a simple redstone gate that pushes the redstone signal forward and restores it to maximum strength.
Right clicking adjusts the delay before the redstone signal is pushed forward.

The comparator is a complex gate that lets you read redstone values from containers.

Placing it with the arrow pointing away from a chest or fluid tank makes it output a redstone signal, with the strength depending on how full the container is.

The humble AND gate takes three inputs and outputs a signal only if all three inputs are on.

If you just need two inputs, simply connect two sides of the gate with a bit of redstone!
The simple OR gate outputs if any of its three inputs are on.

The humble AND gate, with a negation twist! - The output is always on, unless all three inputs are on.

If you just need two inputs, you can connect two of the sides with a bit of redstone!
Simple OR gate with a negation. Output is on, unless any of the three inputs are on.

The eXclusive OR gate sends an output if and only if a single input is on.
This means there will be no output if both inputs are on.

One great feature about this gate is that any change to any input will always invert the output.
This means you could have two levers, each hooked up to one input of the gate, to operate your system, and flipping either of them will always cause a change in the redstone signal.

false XOR false = false
false XOR true = true
true XOR false = true
true XOR true = false

The eXclusive OR gate with a negation.
It will output a signal by unless only a single input is on. If both inputs are on, then the output is also on.

One great feature about this gate is that any change to any input will always invert the output.
This means you could have two levers, each hooked up to one input of the gate, to operate your system, and flipping either of them will always cause a change in the redstone signal.

false XNOR false = true
false XNOR true = false
true XNOR false = false
true XNOR true = true
Buffers have a small delay, before spreading your redstone signal in three directions. This allows you to create compact setups with a 'pulse' of redstone going through it.
Default buffer - simply propagates the signal from the input after a short delay.
Continues the redstone signal after a short delay, and inverts it (turns off redstone that's already on, and vice versa).

Gates with more advanced usage and logic!
This is where we have our first gate with some built-in memory, so you can store a pulse from your system (great for button-operated doors!) and turn it into a steady signal.

The multiplexer has a single output, one input on each side, and a selector on the back.
When the selector input is off, the right-hand input is output, when the selector is on, the left-hand input is used.

The Set-Reset Latch lets you store a redstone signal.

It has two inputs, one on either side, and two primary outputs, front and back.

Whenever an input that was off, is turned on, the latch will keep that side on, acting as an active output on the side.

Additionally, the latch will output a signal to its front or back, when the right or left side of the latch is on.

Turning both left and right on at the same time causes the latch to switch which side it outputs on.

The pulse former has one input and one output.
When the input is on, it makes a quick pulse on the output.

This pulse only happens once, regardless of how long the input is on for
- to make another pulse, the input must turn off, and then back on.

One of the most useful redstone gates.

This simple device generates a redstone pulse on an interval, by default every 1 second.
You can adjust the delay by shift-right clicking the gate.

Whenever the back input of the randomiser pulses on, the three outputs are randomly turned on or off.

The outputs remain on/off until they are turned off/on randomly by a new input signal.

The synchroniser outputs a single short pulse, whenever both its side inputs have been on at least once.

Turning the back input on resets its memory, and requires a new input from both side inputs before it pulses the output again.

For those of you familiar with Tinkers' Construct, you may instinctively want to make a smeltery.

Unfortunately, the smeltery is disabled in this pack, and you'll have to use the melter for your metal melting, tool casting needs.

Don't worry, though, most metals will be worked with in various machines from GregTech, and aren't meltable directly in the melter anyway.

A small tank for combining liquids into alloys.
Automatically drains tanks (including melters!) that are directly touching the alloy tank.

Requires a heat source (either a melter or a tank with lava) underneath it to function.

Acquire flint by breaking gravel.

Later on, you can get flint by breaking it in a mortar.
Simple, reliable, and capable of reinforcement into Wrought Iron or Steel.
Relatively weak on its own, but it is useful for wires, and can be alloyed into bronze to improve its strength.
Rarely useful on its own, Tin is used in very few recipes, and is primarily important as a component of the Bronze alloy.
A soft, precious metal. Used for some advanced components, and for tool part casts.

A strong alloy formed from tin and copper.
Used in low pressure steam machines.

A stronger version of iron made by reheating the iron.
This metal is used in very few machines of the 'ULV' or Ultra Low Voltage variant.

A stronger version of iron made in a blast furnace.
This material is used for high pressure steam and low voltage machines.
A pretty gemstone that can be used for Titanium production in HV GregTech machines.
A 1:1 mix of iron and tin, used in Neutron Reflectors for GregTech nuclear reactors.
A very useful material used for simple logic and even some power transfer!
A combination alloy of copper and redstone that can transport Ultra Low Voltage power without loss.

The 'Red Stone?' quest is intentionally cryptic.
The intention is to give you the tools you need to seek out knowledge on your own.

In order to complete it, you must simply acquire some redstone dust.

To do this, you can right click the Redstone in the Questbook, or search for it in JEI, this lets you see how Redstone is made.

- You should note that it can be made with a GregTech mortar, some stone dust, and dried blood, beetroot, or wildberries.
- Next step is to figure out how to make each of these things.
- The mortar: If you read the 'Crafting Tools' quest in "Getting Started" you should know that tools can be made from a variety of materials, but always show up as Darmstadtium in JEI.
- The stone dust: This one is available by manually using the mortar on a stone button, or...
  If you looked around a bit, you might have noticed it is also available when you crack stone into gravel (or crushed stone) with a hammer.
- The blood, beetroot, or wildberries: This one is tricky
  - The wildberries are intentionally not available yet.
  - The blood comes from the "Heartbeet" which is a random drop when harvesting Beetroot plants, and is then put in a Tinkers' Complement Melter, and then cast in an empty casting table to dry into a ball of coagulated blood.
  - Finally, the beetroot is acquired by simply planting beetroot seeds from Vanilla Minecraft, waiting for them to grow, and harvesting the crop.

Although, if you use JEI, you should find there's a technique that's more resource efficient than simply using a mortar to mix the redstone, involving a melter, casting table, and the same base ingredients.

Redstone is powerful and lets you combine many different behaviours to modify how your machines automate.

Sometimes, it can even be used to create automated farms without any power requirements at all.

The Stencil Table allows you to make wooden patterns for tool parts.
These can then be used in the Part Builder to make individual tool parts, like rods and axe heads!

Time to make some tool parts!
Here you can make the parts required for tools, make the Tool Station to see what parts are required for what tool!
Finally, you get to put all those parts together into a finished tool!
No Description

The Tool Station gives you access to a host of other tools than the ones shown via quests here.

Explore the block's options on your own, and keep in mind that there are sometimes multiple tools for the same general job!
Example: A hatchet and a mattock will both cut wood, but the mattock will let you hoe farmland and also dig up dirt!

The Tinkers' Construct mod provides the blocks necessary for advanced tool construction.

Not only do these tools never break, but their blocks have special properties if they are all connected.

Placing a pattern chest next to a part builder will let you use the patterns directly from the part builder, without needing them in your inventory.

They also have an upgraded Crafting Table, called the Crafting Station.
This block can view and use items from a single adjacent chest, allowing you to have a vastly expanded inventory for crafting - perfect for GregTech crafting tools and other crafting-only materials!

Finally, if the following five blocks are connected, their interfaces will have buttons for quick swapping:
- Stencil Table
- Pattern Chest
- Part Builder
- Tool Station
- Crafting Station

A crook is a tool used to get extra resources from leaves, such as apples, saplings, or silkworms.

If you get a silkworm, you can right click on a leaf block to put it back, where it will slowly conver the leaves into silk leaves!
When the process is done, harvest the silk leaves with a crook to get string.

A handy tool for the budding farmer.

The mattock lets you cut down trees, dig up dirt, and till the dirt into farmland with right click!

A sledge hammer is an excellent tool for smashing rock into smaller bits of rock!

This tool is the quintessential helper for making stone into gravel, gravel into sand, and sand into dust!

Using this unlocks many new explorations of the most basic resource, stone:
- Generation of ores by crushing (cobble-)stone, andesite, diorite, and granite, then sieving the result.
- Making glass, by crushing gravel or crushed granite into sand
- Making clay, by crushing sand into dust, and then soaking it in a barrel of water!
Everything you need to know about sieving!

The humble beginning of sieving!
Here you'll find minerals, saplings, seeds, and stone!
Axes, swords, drills, and more!

Ovens, compressors, crushers, electrolysers and more!
This chapter is sorted by origin mod of various machines and devices, with a special questline for early game to get the player up and running.
Technology without energy or steam requirements!

Materials as you unlock them! Starting from flint, moving through a heck of a lot of metals, rubbers, and plastics!
Most of these are used for tools, but some can be used for new machines, fluid tanks, item containers, and more!

Welcome to Greg Nothing!
This mod pack was designed with the quest book as a helping hand and tutorial from start to finish.
If you are interested in simply getting to the next chapter, follow the quests marked with a special border!
